Bernie versus Trump

Modeling the head-to-head matchup

peter phalen

2/10/2020

library(tidyverse)

Data prep

Get data directly from 538

data <- read_csv("https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/polls-page/president_polls.csv")

And process everything.

data <- 
  data %>% 
  subset(is.na(state))  # national polls only

data$candidate_name <- factor(data$candidate_name)
  

# get sanders head-to-heads
sanders_rows <- which(data$candidate_name == "Bernard Sanders")
sanders_rows <- lapply(sanders_rows, function(x){seq(x, x + 1)})
sanders_rows <- do.call("c", sanders_rows)
data <- data[sanders_rows,] 

# get rid of minor candidates
pence_rows <- which(data$candidate_name == "Mike Pence")
sanders_v_pence_rows <- c(pence_rows, pence_rows - 1) 
data <- data %>% slice(-sanders_v_pence_rows)

haley_rows <- which(data$candidate_name == "Nimrata R. Haley")
sanders_v_haley_rows <- c(haley_rows, haley_rows - 1) 
data <- data %>% slice(-sanders_v_haley_rows)

# encode dates as... dates
data <- data %>%
  transform(start_date = as.Date(data$start_date, format = "%m/%d/%y"),
         end_date = as.Date(data$end_date, format = "%m/%d/%y"))

# polls are usually conducted over multiple days
# get the point midway between the start and end dates of each poll
data$date <- data$start_date + floor((data$end_date-data$start_date)/2)

# also get a data frame just for Bernie
bern <- data %>% subset(candidate_name == "Bernard Sanders")

Plot some results

First we just take a rough look at how Bernie seems to be doing against Trump.

data %>% 
  # relevel just for the color scheme
  transform(candidate = relevel(candidate_name, ref="Donald Trump")) %>%
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = date, y = pct, color = candidate) + 
  geom_point() + 
  labs(caption="Data from 538")+
  ggtitle("Bernie Sanders v. Trump", subtitle="head-to-head polling") +
  geom_smooth() +  
  ylab("percent support")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

These datapoints come from many different polling companies. Different polling companies tend to have biases, if only due to methodological differences. It’s worth checking for these so-called “house effects.”

bern %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = date, y = pct, color = pollster) + 
  geom_point() + 
  ggtitle("Bernie Sanders (v. Trump)", subtitle="colored by pollster") +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  ylab("percent support") + 
  scale_x_date(date_labels="%b") +
  facet_wrap(~pollster, scales = "fixed")

House effects are clearly visible in these graphs. For example, Emerson College seems to show consistently better results for Bernie than Fox News over the same period of time. We’ll want to account for this in our model.

bern %>% 
  subset(pollster %in% c("Fox News/Beacon Research/Shaw & Co. Research", 
                         "Emerson College")) %>%
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = date, y = pct) + 
  geom_point() + 
  ylim(30,60) +
  ggtitle("Bernie Sanders (v. Trump)", subtitle="colored by pollster") +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  ylab("percent support") + 
  facet_wrap(~pollster, scales = "fixed")
